"Dulamsuren C., Hauck M., Leuschner H.H., Leuschner C.","Climate response of tree-ring width in Larix sibirica growing in the drought-stressed forest-steppe ecotone of northern Mongolia",2011,"Annals of Forest Science","68","2",,"275","282",,,10.1007/s13595-011-0043-9,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-80051479874&partnerID=40&md5=02ad366d33572b12ec0aa677a2839a05","Department of Plant Ecology, Albrecht von Haller Institute of Plant Sciences, University of Göttingen, Untere Karspüle 2, 37073 Göttingen, Germany; Department of Palynology and Climate Dynamics, Albrecht von Haller Institute of Plant Sciences, University of Göttingen, Untere Karspüle 2, 37073 Göttingen, Germany","Dulamsuren, C., Department of Plant Ecology, Albrecht von Haller Institute of Plant Sciences, University of Göttingen, Untere Karspüle 2, 37073 Göttingen, Germany; Hauck, M., Department of Plant Ecology, Albrecht von Haller Institute of Plant Sciences, University of Göttingen, Untere Karspüle 2, 37073 Göttingen, Germany; Leuschner, H.H., Department of Palynology and Climate Dynamics, Albrecht von Haller Institute of Plant Sciences, University of Göttingen, Untere Karspüle 2, 37073 Göttingen, Germany; Leuschner, C., Department of Plant Ecology, Albrecht von Haller Institute of Plant Sciences, University of Göttingen, Untere Karspüle 2, 37073 Göttingen, Germany","Introduction: Siberian larch (Larix sibirica) has its southern distribution limit in Mongolia in an area of rapidly rising temperatures. Direct effects of climate on tree-ring formation due to drought stress or indirect effects via the control of insect herbivore populations are little studied. Methods: The hypotheses were tested that stem increment of Siberian larch is reduced by (1) drought during the growing season and (2) high snow cover, as the latter is thought to protect hibernating herbivores, including gypsy moth (Lymantria dispar). Results: Tree-ring width increases with decreasing summer temperature, increasing precipitation during the growing season and decreasing winter precipitation. Conclusions: The susceptibility of stem wood formation to drought during the growing season suggests that a future climate warming will decrease productivity of Siberian larch, thus affecting its existence within the forest-steppe ecotone of Mongolia. Narrow tree rings in years following winters with low snowfall support the hypothesis that winter precipitation exerts an indirect effect on the growth of Siberian larch by controlling the survival rates of gypsy moth eggs. © The Author(s) 2011.","Forest-steppe ecotone; Global warming; Larix sibirica; Lymantria dispar; Tree-ring analysis","deciduous tree; drought stress; ecosystem response; ecotone; global warming; growing season; herbivore; limiting factor; moth; pest control; plant-herbivore interaction; population distribution; population structure; precipitation (climatology); primary production; snow; snow cover; steppe; temperature effect; tree ring; Mongolia; Hexapoda; Larix; Larix sibirica; Lymantria; Lymantria dispar",,,,,,"Andresen, J.A., McCullough, D.G., Potter, B.E., Koller, C.N., Bauer, L.S., Lusch, D.P., Ramm, C.W., Effects of winter temperatures on gypsy moth egg masses in the Great Lakes region of the United States (2001) Agricultural and Forest Meteorology, 110 (2), pp. 85-100. , DOI 10.1016/S0168-1923(01)00282-9, PII S0168192301002829; Batima, P., Natsagdorj, L., Gombluudev, P., Erdenetsetseg, B., Observed climate change in Mongolia (2005) Assessments of Impacts and Adaptations of Climate Change Workings Papers No. 12, p. 26. , International START Secretariat Washington DC; Bräuning, A., Zur dendroklimatologie hochtibets während des letzten jahrtausends (1999) Diss Bot, 312, pp. 1-164; Carrer, M., Urbinati, C., Age-dependent tree-ring growth responses to climate in Larix decidua and Pinus cembra (2004) Ecology, 85 (3), pp. 730-740; Cook, E.R., (1985) A Time Series Analysis Approach to Tree Ring Standardization, p. 171. , PhD